g.text: Audrey LY Chang*, Hannah M Selwyn*, Daniel J Garside, Josh Fuller-Deets, Shriya M Awasthi, Bevil R Conway

text.tspan: Categorization is a hallmark of high-level cognition.
Memories get biased towards categorical representations in humans.
We can use this knowledge to examine whether macaques have color categories like humans do.
This is valuable to know for the interpretation of neurophysiological data, and also to test theories about categorization in humans.

g.text: All animals have high accuracy on easy trials.

text.tspan: trichromatic primates innately categorize colors into two essential categories
color categories reflect differences in color use across species and cultures.

g.text: We find evidence for 2 shared color categories - a cool color and a warm color.
